SHOW BINARY LOGS;

ðŸ“‚ 2. Use mysqlbinlog to read the logs
Run this from the command line (not inside MySQL):

mysqlbinlog /var/lib/mysql/binlog.000001

mysqlbinlog --verbose --database=SSO /var/lib/mysql/binlog.000005


ðŸ“„ 3. Filter by date or time
You can read a binlog for a specific time range:

mysqlbinlog --start-datetime="2025-07-23 10:00:00" \
            --stop-datetime="2025-07-23 11:00:00" \
            /var/lib/mysql/binlog.000002


 4. Filter for a specific database
To filter output by database name:

mysqlbinlog --database=your_database /var/lib/mysql/binlog.000002


ðŸ“¦ 5. Find binlog directory
If you're not sure where binlogs are stored, check this in MySQL:

SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'log_bin_basename';


## Read the bin-log file in windows server ##

# Use mysqlbinlog to Read the Log

mysqlbinlog -v "C:\Path\To\BinaryLogs\MASTER-bin.000002"

Optional â€“ Filter by Time or Position
By position:
mysqlbinlog --start-position=154 --stop-position=900 "C:\...\MASTER-bin.000002"

By datetime:
mysqlbinlog --start-datetime="2025-07-25 10:00:00" --stop-datetime="2025-07-25 11:00:00" "C:\...\MASTER-bin.000002"


 # Optional â€“ Save Output to File
mysqlbinlog "C:\...\MASTER-bin.000002" > C:\logs\binlog_output.sql

# (Optional) Replay the Binary Log
# If you want to apply the binary log contents to a MySQL server:
mysql -u root -p < C:\logs\binlog_output.sql





